# Monitor GitHub Actions After Every Push

After any push to GitHub, treat workflow monitoring as required follow-through.

## Required behavior

- Identify the pushed commit/branch and immediately check GitHub Actions runs triggered by that push.
- Continue monitoring until all workflows for that push reach a terminal state.
- Treat `Render Preview Attestation Gate` failures as merge blockers: fix PR title (`[render preview]`) and refresh `.ci/render-live-attestation.json` with passing live checks.
- After pushes that affect Render-backed PR previews, use **Render MCP** to confirm preview services reached a **terminal live** state (and to capture service URLs / deploy ids for attestation refresh): **`list_services`** with **`includePreviews`: true**, then **`list_deploys`** / **`get_deploy`**; use **`list_logs`** when a deploy fails. Prefer server **`project-0-vecinita-render`** when available, else **`plugin-render-render`** per workspace rules in **render-deploy-monitor-and-debug**.
- If any workflow fails, investigate logs and fix the root cause locally (not a workaround-only patch).
- Re-run local validation (`make ci` from repository root) before pushing the fix.
- Push fixes and repeat monitor -> diagnose -> fix until all workflows for the latest push pass.

## Completion gate

- Do not mark work complete or ready while relevant GitHub Actions checks for the latest pushed commit are failing or still running.
- If blocked by external/manual dependencies, clearly report the blocker and the next required user action.

## Example flow

```bash
git push
gh run list --commit <sha>
gh run watch <run-id>
# if failed:
gh run view <run-id> --log-failed
make ci
git push
```
